post_text:
Congratulations to Jennifer Feliciano, Graphic Arts Teacher at Thomas Jefferson Arts Academy, whose work has been selected as part of Rockefeller Center’s Flag Project. Out of over 1000 artists who contributed designs that celebrate the diverse culture, vibrant energy, and strength of New York City, Mrs. Feliciano’s piece was among those selected to be flown in a temporary art installation on the 193 poles surrounding the iconic Rink at Rockefeller Center. Mrs. Feliciano’s notes in her flag design description:

I am passionate about visual communications and the way imagery affects our world. I believe it should ignite conversation and create a way for people to connect through it. This design is a representation of creating connections; of crossing paths along the journey of everyday life and meeting others to share insights, dreams, dinner or a cab ride. This is what New York means to me: it is a place where I can enjoy the mundane and the novelty of the tourists and pause in the midst of the fast-paced environment and connect with them both.

I am passionate about visual communications and the way imagery affects our world. I believe it should ignite conversation and create a way for people to connect through it. This design is a representation of creating connections; of crossing paths along the journey of everyday life and meeting others to share insights, dreams, dinner or a cab ride. #epscommunityconnect

Guidelines for open Zoom dance class

1. Be on time for your scheduled class. Once in progress, we must stick to the time slot for each class.

2. Student devices will be on MUTE unless you need to ask or answer a question in the “Chat” Room.

3. All participants must be appropriately dressed.

4. Proper classroom behavior is expected.

5. Interactions will occur between the teacher & students or students & students. Parents will not be permitted to participate directly in the class but can help out outside of video view.

6. If parents would like to contact us please reach out to the Department of Recreation at (908) 820-4220 leave a message and we will return your phone call.

post_text:
More than 7,900 members of our Elizabeth School District community tuned in to Facebook Live Monday for "Reopening Together," the first step in studying the options for safely resuming school in September.

More than 1,800 community members commented on the initial presentation by Superintendent Olga Hugelmeyer. The presentation discussed options within the parameters ordered by Governor Phil Murphy and the state Department of Education related to COVID19. You can read details of Reopening Together here:
https://www.epsnj.org/Page/4096

We want to hear more of your input so it's critical that you respond to a brief parent survey here:
English Survey
https://forms.gle/dxkkcDh1Z2EAZ3jm7
Spanish Survey
https://forms.gle/qtPTBJ5hcU8txyR97

Board of Education President Diane Barbosa said the district will continue to seek community stakeholder comment through early August before a plan is submitted on August 11th.

Pictured: Superintendent Hugelmeyer and Board of Education President Diane Barbosa during Monday's Facebook Live presentation.

post_text:
Elizabeth Public Schools Celebrates Portugal Day

Each year on June 10, the Elizabeth Public Schools learning community and people throughout the world celebrate Portugal Day. The holiday is observed on June 10 in honor of Luís de Camões, a Portuguese poet and literary icon who wrote Os Lusíadas, a noted poem celebrating Portuguese history, including 15th-century Portuguese explorations which brought fame and fortune to the country.

In celebration of Portugal Day, Elizabeth Public Schools would like to recognize all members of our learning community and greater community of Portuguese heritage for their meaningful contributions toward making Elizabeth's schools and neighborhoods so special and unique.

post_text:
EPS Celebrates Haitian Flag Day

Flag Day has been a major holiday in Haiti since 1803, when the revolutionary leader Jean-Jacques Dessalines tore up a French tricolor and had his goddaughter, Catherine Flon, stitch together the country’s first independent flag. The new banner consisted of just a red and a blue stripe, without the central white stripe of the tricolor.

On this day in 1803, the first purely Haitian flag was adopted on the last day of the Congress of Arcahaie.

It was not until January 1, 1804, that Haiti officially declared independence from France, becoming the first free state in the Caribbean liberated and governed by its former slaves. That revolutionary spirit is still a source of national pride and celebration today.

Elizabeth Public Schools, as part of Haitian Flag Day and Haitian-American Heritage Month, would like to recognize all of its team members and families, as well as all greater Elizabeth community members, of Haitian descent for their tremendous contributions to the culture and vibrance of Elizabeth's schools and neighborhoods.

post_text:
Honoring Our Nurses During National Nurses Week

In recognition of National Nurses Week (May 6 - May 12), Elizabeth Public Schools and the Elizabeth Board of Education would like to show their greatest appreciation for the excellent work Elizabeth Public Schools nurses perform each day to support success in our schools by ensuring our students and team members are healthy to perform at high levels as well as the work they are currently doing in the community to help in the battle against COVID-19.

Additionally, EPS and the Board would like to express its tremendous gratitude for nurses everywhere for the inspiring, courageous, and extraordinary work you perform each day to help care for and save so many lives. Your service and sacrifices, especially during these uncertain times of the COVID-19 pandemic, are appreciated more than words could possibly express.

post_text:
EPS Among 754 Districts In the Nation Named 2020 Best Communities for Music Education by NAMM Foundation

Congratulations to Elizabeth Public Schools for being among 754 school districts recognized as the Best Communities in the nation for music education. The award program recognizes outstanding efforts by teachers, administrators, parents, students and community leaders who have made music education part of a well-rounded education. Designations are made to districts and schools that demonstrate an exceptionally high commitment and access to music education.

post_text:
Elizabeth Public Schools remains closed in accordance with Governor Murphy’s stay at home order. Elizabeth Public Schools is canceling plans to observe spring recess and has officially revised the 2019-2020 school calendar. The Elizabeth Board of Education voted unanimously last night to continue to hold school virtually Tuesday, April 14, through Friday, April 17. It is important that we continue to support all of our students with consistency. Please note that Easter recess will be observed on Friday, April 10th and Monday, April 13th. E-Remote Learning will not take place on these two dates in observance of the holiday.

See PDF @ https://www.epsnj.org/cms/lib/NJ01912667/Centricity/shared/calendars/SchoolCalendars2019-2020.pdf

post_text:
NJSIAA Basketball Tournament-IMPORTANT Release

UPDATED NJSIAA STATEMENT - Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) (3/12/2020, 10 PM)

“The NJSIAA has canceled the remainder of the boys and girls basketball championships. The games will not be rescheduled.

“We have been making our decisions one day at a time, taking into account the best available guidance from the state health department and the CDC. Now, given the rapidly changing circumstances and uncertainties facing our member schools, our student-athletes, our host facilities, and many others, we no longer see a viable path to the completion of the Group Championships on Saturday and Sunday.

“We understand that our decision will disappoint many, but believe it to be in the best interest of our student-athletes and all those involved with the games.”

Thanks to everyone, for all you do and have done for our student-athletes!

Respectfully,

Al Stumpf and Kim DeGraw-Cole

Elizabeth Athletics

Jerome Dunn Academy School No.9
February 26 at 2:35 PM ·

As a School of Character, Jerome Dunn Academy celebrates scholars who exhibit good character; every month we honor a different character pillar. For the month of January, we celebrate COMPASSION. Each homeroom teacher selected a scholar who demonstrated compassion throughout the month. Below are our Scholars of Compassion. Each scholar dined with our school Principal, Ms. Torres. In addition, they all received the "Kids of Character" pin.

For the month of February we are recognizing the pillar of LOVE. The scholar of compassion will help their teacher select the scholar of LOVE. We will continue this celebration each month.

Elizabeth Athletics added 27 new photos to the album: Senior Night @ the Dunn Sport Center — at Dunn Sports Center.
February 20 at 11:09 AM · Elizabeth, NJ ·

Seniors Jordan Price, DJ Watkins, Kamar Thomas, Antonie Burton, Nas Mcmillion and Franklin Gomera of the No. 4 Elizabeth Varsity Boys Basketball team were honored before their matchup against No. 9 St. Peter’s Prep at Thomas G. Dunn Sport Center. Price and Watkins were also honored for reaching the 1,000 point milestone in their Minutemen career. The Minutemen defeated St. Peter’s Prep 49-42 behind 13 points and seven rebounds from Jayden Pierre and 10 points and five rebounds from Price.

Also honored where senior cheerleader's Shakeenah Brooks and Anasia Clark.

Congratulations to all the Minutemen seniors and to the team for their victory against St. Peter’s. Go Minutemen! #EHSMinutemen

Major Congratulations to EHS swimmer, Alfredo Rojas for breaking the school record in the 100 Yd. Butterfly in the time of 55.18. Rojas has now broken every individual swimming record in Elizabeth High School history! He also is a member of 2 record holding relay teams and is considered EHS’s greatest swimmer ever! The entire team and staff are very proud of Alfredo’s hard work and accomplishments. His accomplishments are well earned and well deserved. Next goal for Alfredo… qualifying for the NJ Meet of Champions. #GoEHS

EHS Classic is free channel devoted to showcasing the rich tradition of Elizabeth Athletics. It is dedicated to telecasting many of Elizabeth HS's greatest games from the 70's, 80’s, 90’s and early 2000's.

Please subscribe, like, and share our page to spread the news!

Donations appreciated… If anyone has a memorable game on VHS tape or DVD that they would like to donate to the library, we’ll copy the tape/DVD and return it to you within 3 business days. You may contact us at ehsathletics@epsnj.org

Thank you in advance for your support.

The Union County Immunization Clinic at 40 Parker Rd. in Elizabeth will have extended hours on Tuesday, January 7 and Thursday, January 9 from 3:30-6:30pm. For walk-ins the clinic is extending the hours to accommodate those children that are in need of the flu vaccination to attend school.

Please be advised to participate in the free program you must either have no insurance or have Medicaid Plan A.

• Bring immunization record
• Birth Certificate
• Parents ID
• Proof of Address ie: lease, electric or gas bill

post_text: On Saturday, Dec. 21, members of the Elizabeth Police Department, Elizabeth Fire Department, City Hall, and the Thomas Jefferson Arts Academy PTO gathered at Jefferson Arts to connect victims of the recent Westfield Avenue fire with representatives from the US Marine Corps Toys for Tots. The event provided holiday gifts for children from four impacted families. Our heartfelt thanks go out to the Marine Toys for Tots organization for their support of our families, and to the Elizabeth Police Department, Elizabeth Fire Department, City Hall, and Jefferson Arts PTO for organizing the event!

post_text: On December 5, Hamilton Preparatory Academy hosted an AVID Showcase. The event was well attended by in district staff as well as AVID practitioners from local schools, New York , and Connecticut. The day highlighted AVID strategies within the classroom, the schools focus on creating a positive culture of college awareness, and a commitment in involving parents in the education of their children. Participants visited numerous classrooms, heard from staff, students, and parents on the positive impact the AVID system has played in making college a reality. The day placed a spotlight on the great things happening at Hamilton. This was the second Showcase hosted by Hamilton, and the staff as well as AVID Center is looking forward to the next opportunity for Hamilton to open its doors to the extended AVID family.
